Spring — Dependency Injection & XML Config (Notes Summary)

📌 Image 1 — IoC Container Deep Dive

### Object → Bean
In Spring, any object managed by the IoC container is called a Bean

```
Your Java Class  →  registered in XML config  →  Spring creates it  →  it becomes a Bean
```

---

IoC Container — Two Implementations

| Interface | Description |
|--------------------|---------------------------------------|
| BeanFactory        | Basic container, lazy loading (older) |
| ApplicationContext | Advanced container, extends BeanFactory — use this always|

Both live on the JVM Heap.

---

#### How the Container Works

```
20 Classes in your project
        ↓
You pick 15 (that Spring should manage)
        ↓
Register them in XML Configuration file (beans.xml)
        ↓
e.g., <bean id="st1" class="com.example.Student"/>
        ↓
IoC Container creates & manages those objects → called "Managed Beans"
```

The diagram shows:
- The outer blue box = JVM
- The inner green box = IoC Container / ApplicationContext
- Inside it: `Student` bean with object `st1` → this is a **managed bean**
- You get this bean via `ApplicationContext` → no `new` keyword needed

---

#### XML Configuration Flow

```
Student.java          beans.xml (config file)
────────────    →     <bean id="st1" class="Student"/>
class Student {}      
                  ↓
         ApplicationContext ctx = 
           new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext("beans.xml");
         Student s = (Student) ctx.getBean("st1");
```

---

### 🔑 Key Terminology Locked In

| Term | Meaning |
|---|---|
|     Bean    | Any object managed by Spring's IoC container |
| BeanFactory | Basic IoC container |
| ApplicationContext | Full-featured IoC container (preferred) |
| Managed Bean | Bean whose lifecycle Spring controls |
| XML Config | The file where you declare which classes become beans |

---

### 💡 Why XML Config (old-style)?
This is the classic Spring way — before annotations (`@Component`, `@Bean`) existed. Understanding this helps you grasp why annotations were introduced — they replaced verbose XML with concise declarative config. Interviewers sometimes ask this to test Spring fundamentals depth.
